{"parse":{"title":"Phallocentrism","pageid":3496839,"revid":853065087,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Phallocentrism</b> is the ideology that the <a href=\"/wiki/Phallus\" title=\"Phallus\">phallus</a>, or <a href=\"/wiki/Male\" title=\"Male\">male</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Sex\" title=\"Sex\">sexual</a> organ, is the central element in the organization of the social world. Phallocentrism has been analyzed in literary criticism, psychoanalysis and psychology, linguistics, medicine and health care, and philosophy. \n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#First_phase\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">First phase</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Second_phase\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Second phase</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Third_phase\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Third phase</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"First_phase\">First phase</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phallocentrism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: First phase\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The term was coined in 1927 by <a href=\"/wiki/Ernest_Jones\" title=\"Ernest Jones\">Ernest Jones</a>, as part of his debate with <a href=\"/wiki/Freud\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Freud\">Freud</a> over the role of the <a href=\"/wiki/Phallic_stage\" title=\"Phallic stage\">phallic stage</a> in childhood development, when he argued that \u201cmen analysts have been led to adopt an unduly phallo-centric view\u201d.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Drawing on the earlier arguments of <a href=\"/wiki/Karen_Horney\" title=\"Karen Horney\">Karen Horney</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Jones, in a series of articles, maintained the position that women were not disappointed creatures driven by <a href=\"/wiki/Penis_envy\" title=\"Penis envy\">penis envy</a>. Instead, this belief was itself a theoretical defense against <a href=\"/wiki/Castration_anxiety\" title=\"Castration anxiety\">castration anxiety</a>.  Freud, however, remained unmoved in his opposition to the Horney/Jones thesis,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and his was the predominant psychoanalytic position thereafter, though some like <a href=\"/wiki/Janet_Malcolm\" title=\"Janet Malcolm\">Janet Malcolm</a> would modify his position to the effect that \u201cFreud's concept, of course, is... a <i>description</i> of phallocentrism, not a recommendation of it\u201d.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Second_phase\">Second phase</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phallocentrism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Second phase\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Jacques_Lacan\" title=\"Jacques Lacan\">Jacques Lacan</a> added a linguistic turn to the debate with his article \u201cThe Signification of the Phallus\u201d (1958/65), arguing that the phallus was not a <a href=\"/wiki/Object_relations_theory\" title=\"Object relations theory\">part-object</a>, an imaginary object, or a physical organ, but rather \u201cthe signifier intended to designate as a whole the effects of the signifier... this signifying function of the phallus\u201d.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Jacques_Derrida\" title=\"Jacques Derrida\">Jacques Derrida</a> challenged his thesis as phallocentric, and the charge was taken up by <a href=\"/wiki/Second-wave_feminism\" title=\"Second-wave feminism\">second-wave feminism</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> extending the focus of protest from Lacan to Freud,<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> psychoanalysis, and male-centered thinking as a whole:<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> the way that \u201c[t]he phallus, centre of meaning, became man's identity with himself... a masculine symbolic\u201d.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>However conflict arose within feminism over the issue.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Some French feminists, seeing phallocentrism and feminism as two sides of the same coin, sought to make a postphallicist breakthrough.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>  Others, like the English feminist <a href=\"/wiki/Jacqueline_Rose\" title=\"Jacqueline Rose\">Jacqueline Rose</a>, while accepting that \u201cLacan was implicated in the phallocentrism he described,\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> nevertheless considered his analysis as important for an understanding of how women were constituted as a split subject in society.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Third_phase\">Third phase</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phallocentrism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Third phase\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>From a <a href=\"/wiki/Postcolonial\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Postcolonial\">postcolonial</a> perspective, however, such theoretical debates revealed the irrelevance of first world feminists, with their phallocentric preoccupations, to the ordinary life of the <a href=\"/wiki/Subaltern_(postcolonialism)\" title=\"Subaltern (postcolonialism)\">subaltern</a> woman in the Third World;<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> and <a href=\"/wiki/Third-wave_feminism\" title=\"Third-wave feminism\">Third-wave feminism</a>, with its concern for the marginalised, the particular, and for <a href=\"/wiki/Intersectionality\" title=\"Intersectionality\">intersectionality</a>, has also broadly seen the theoreticism and essentialism of feminism's earlier concern for phallocentrism as irrelevant to daily female experience.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Gayatri_Spivak\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gayatri Spivak\">Gayatri Spivak</a> suggests that feminism needs to negotiate an accommodation with phallocentrism.<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phallocentrism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"div-col columns column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 22em; -webkit-column-width: 22em; column-width: 22em;\">\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Androcentrism\" title=\"Androcentrism\">Androcentrism</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Ecriture_feminine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ecriture feminine\">Ecriture feminine</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Feminist_geography\" title=\"Feminist geography\">Feminist geography</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Gynocriticism\" title=\"Gynocriticism\">Gynocriticism</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Julia_Kristeva\" title=\"Julia Kristeva\">Julia Kristeva</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Male_gaze\" title=\"Male gaze\">Male gaze</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Phallic_architecture\" title=\"Phallic architecture\">Phallic architecture</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Phallic_monism\" title=\"Phallic monism\">Phallic monism</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Phallogocentrism\" title=\"Phallogocentrism\">Phallogocentrism</a></li></ul></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phallocentrism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Quoted in K. K. Reithven, <i>Feminist Literary Studies</i> (1990) p. 54</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_re